'''Neymar da Silva Santos Júnior''' ({{IPA|pt-br|nejˈmaʁ dɐ ˈsiwvɐ ˈsɐ̃tuz ˈʒuni.oʁ|audio=Neymar pronunciation.mp3}}<!--This is an IPA transcription based on the actual pronunciation and following [[MOS:PRON]] and [[H:IPA-PT]]. Please do not remove it.-->; born 5 February 1992), simply known as '''Neymar Júnior''' (shortened to '''Neymar Jr''') or mononymously as '''Neymar''', is a Brazilian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] or a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Campeonato Brasileiro Série A]] club [[Santos FC|Santos]], which he [[Captain (association football)|captains]], and the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]]. Known for his dribbling, technical ability, playmaking, and finishing, he is widely regarded as one of the greatest players of all time. He is one of only five players to have scored 100 goals with three different clubs,{{efn|group=lower-greek|The other four players are [[Isidro Lángara]], [[Romário]], [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], and [[Robert Lewandowski]].}}  both the all-time Brazilian top goalscorer (43) and [[UEFA Champions League#Most assists|assist provider]] (33) in the [[UEFA Champions League]], ranks second for the [[List of men's footballers with 50 or more international goals|all-time South American men's top goalscorers]] in international football (79), and was the [[Assist (association football)#Players with most assists in international football (all-time)|all-time top assist provider]] in international football (59) from 2023 to 2025.{{efn|group=lower-greek|From October 2023 to October 2025.}}

Neymar made his professional debut with Santos in 2009. In 2011, he led the club to the [[Copa Libertadores]], ending a 48-year drought for the title. In 2013, [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] signed him and he soon became part of a dominant attacking trio with [[Lionel Messi]] and [[Luis Suárez]]—known as ''MSN''. In [[2014–15 FC Barcelona season|2014–15]], Neymar won the [[Treble (association football)|treble]] of [[La Liga]], the [[Copa del Rey]], and the [[2014–15 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], finishing as the top goalscorer of both that season's Champions League and the Copa del Rey.{{efn|group=lower-greek|[[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Lionel Messi]] were also the top goal scorers of the Champions League campaign, with all three each scoring 10 goals.}} In the following [[2015–16 FC Barcelona season|season]], he helped Barcelona win the [[Double (association football)|double]]. At Barcelona, Neymar was prevented from winning the [[Ballon d'Or|Ballon d’Or]] by the [[Messi–Ronaldo rivalry|Messi'''–'''Ronaldo]] dominance, finishing third in both [[2015 FIFA Ballon d'Or|2015]] and [[2017 Ballon d'Or|2017]].

In 2017, Neymar left Barcelona to join [[Paris Saint-Germain FC|Paris Saint-Germain]], becoming the [[List of most expensive association football transfers|most expensive player in history]] after his €222&nbsp;million release clause was activated.{{efn|group=lower-greek|Although Barcelona did not classify Neymar's €222 million buyout clause as a transfer fee, it was functionally identical to a transfer fee, since it cancelled his then-current contract with Barcelona (as in a typical transfer). The payment, provided by an unknown source, made him the most expensive football player.<ref name="FCB Neymar">{{cite press release|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2017-2018/fc-barcelona-communique-on-neymar-jr-buyout-clause|title=FC Barcelona communiqué on Neymar Jr|date=3 August 2017|access-date=3 August 2017|publisher=FC Barcelona|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803171515/https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2017-2018/fc-barcelona-communique-on-neymar-jr-buyout-clause|archive-date=3 August 2017}}</ref><ref name="BBC Neymar">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40762417|title=Neymar: Paris St-Germain sign Barcelona forward for world record 222m euros|date=3 August 2017|access-date=4 August 2017|publisher=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803235435/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40762417|archive-date=3 August 2017}}</ref>}} From 2018 onwards, injuries hampered Neymar's career, causing limited game time. Despite this, he was instrumental to PSG retrieving the [[2017–18 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]] title in his [[2017–18 Paris Saint-Germain FC season|debut season]] and was named [[Ligue 1 Player of the Year]], led them to their first-ever [[2020 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]] in 2020, became their [[List of Paris Saint-Germain FC records and statistics#All-time top scorers|fourth all-time top goalscorer]], and won four more [[Ligue 1]] titles, as well as three [[Coupe de France]] titles. In 2023, he joined Saudi club [[Al Hilal SFC|Al-Hilal]] before returning to Santos in January 2025.

At 18, Neymar debuted for Brazil and has since become the nation's [[Brazil national football team#Most capped players|second-most-capped player]], only trailing [[Cafu]]. He is the nation's [[Brazil national football team#Top goalscorers|all-time top goalscorer]], with [[List of international goals scored by Neymar|79 goals]] in 128 matches. Neymar won the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup]] and received the [[Golden Ball (FIFA Confederations Cup)|Golden Ball]] before being voted in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup#Dream Team|Dream Team]] and receiving the [[FIFA World Cup Bronze Boot|Bronze Boot]] at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]. In [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016]], he captained Brazil to their first [[Olympic gold medal]] in [[Football at the Summer Olympics|men's football]] at the [[Summer Olympic Games|Summer Olympics]], having previously won silver in the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2012 edition]]. In the [[2021 Copa América]], he was focal to Brazil's [[2021 Copa América final|runners-up]] finish, where he was jointly awarded [[2021 Copa América#Awards|Best Player]]. In 2023, he surpassed [[Pelé]]'s 52-year long record as Brazil's all-time top goalscorer.

